│ THOUGHT: The fix didn't work because the TreeEntry for the PHI nodes doesn't have `getOpcode() == Instruction::PHI`. As I suspected earlier, the `getOpcode()` returns the opcode of  │
│ the main operation, which in this case is an `add` instruction (`%1` or `%2`) referenced by the PHI, not the PHI itself.                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                                                                       │
│ The real issue is that the TreeEntry is created for the values used by the stores, which are the PHI nodes in `bb2`, but these PHI nodes reference other PHI nodes in block `%3`,     │
│ which in turn reference the `add` instructions. So the TreeEntry's main operation ends up being the `add` instruction.                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                       │
│ I need to check if the TreeEntry contains any PHI nodes, not just if its main operation is a PHI. Let me modify the condition to check if any of the scalars are PHI nodes.           │
│                                                                                                                                                                                       │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                               │
│ cd /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize && sed -i '15096a\  // Handle entries containing PHI nodes specially since their operands can be from different         │
│ blocks.\n  if (any_of(E->Scalars, IsaPred<PHINode>)) {\n    Res = FindLastInst();\n    return *Res;\n  }' SLPVectorizer.cpp                                                           │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                   │
